<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="ac680a54a4637c3b1c00613f3aea382f" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Gods of Combat: Part 1 - the Fellowship<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.69)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10894'>Alex "Worlds" Weavers</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10894&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 19, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Disclaimer: This article is intended for awesome, but not gaurenteed to have or be awesome within itself.  This article is intended to be a deep analysis of what goes into the thought process of a skirmish, and the importance of various numbers involved in combat.  I haven&#39;t gotten my King box yet (shutup) so I&#39;m not going to discuss RotK Threat and Initiative strategies here, but I will include tie-ins to such (especially initiative).<br />
<br />
Now that that&#39;s over, you&#39;re all asking yourself, so what&#39;s this punk kid know about skirmishes that we don&#39;t?<br />
<br />
The answer is, probably nothing.  Most everyone still here probably knows everything I am going to say, as we&#39;re all experienced players, but I don&#39;t think very many have taken the time to think it all over.  For instance, why is 8 strength so much better than 7, but 9 not that much better than 8?  Why is an exertion preferable to a wound, and when should I chump block Merry?<br />
<br />
I&#39;ll try to answer all of these questions, as well as many more, with examples from high level decks and starter decks, however, always remember this (and I cannot stress this enough) - the skirmish phase is only as complicated as what you have in your hand, your opponent has in his hand, and what&#39;s on the table - it&#39;s the assignment phase that counts.<br />
-<br />
<br />
I. The Fellowship Phase<br />
The Fellowship phase is the spot, in most top-level decks, that determines the outcome of all skirmishes.  It&#39;s where you play weapons, and armor, and create your options in the skirmish phase.  Each card that you play is in exchange for an amount of twilight that gives your opponent an opportunity to play his minions, weapons, conditions, and events, and thus there is balance.<br />
<br />
You&#39;re the free peoples player.  You want cascading unbalance in your fellowship&#39;s favor.  Choose cards that play in this phase that give you the most bonus for the least cost - for instance, cards that require an exertion rarely cost more than 1, and so long as you&#39;re not losing your skirmishes, you can dish out as many of those as you wish - unless you need the vitality for other, more powerful exertions later.  Most weapons also cost one and give permenant strength and damage enhancements, which is why they are so commonly used - after all, what is Aragorn without his sword.<br />
<br />
Conditions are often the glue that binds together a Free People&#39;s side, however, they can often be a burden, with their high twilight cost.  Cool effects, but always vulnerable and always with consequences.  I recommend a FP side that can function well without them, but kill most everything with them.  Remember - the best conditions for your deck are not always the ones that fit your theme, and are not always the generic throw ins - solve your deck&#39;s problems.<br />
<br />
Discard your opponents permenants.  Condition removal is next to loving Jesus and regular showering.  Remember - permenance is what the Free People&#39;s player has, and the shadow player does not.  If all you give your opponent is a pile of pool each turn, but keep his support cards out of play, odds are you will come out on top, every time.<br />
<br />
The most important choice of all, however, is your choice of the 9 companions that come with your deck.  Since you can start a maximum of 4, but should generally run 5 for swarm protection and have some backups in case somebody dies, it&#39;s usually a good idea to run at least 6 different companions, however, as proved by Mike Dalton, you can run only 2 and live forever, so do what you will.  9 Companions gives you the versatality to lose a skirmish how you want it lost, but also tends to leak pool like an old man.  So how do you find out what is right for your deck?<br />
<br />
Well, most decks start off with a choice of a main, or several mains, to base the deck around.  This is a very good way to build a deck, however, only playtesting can show if your mains can hold up under the strain of high level competition.  In general, the 5 companions from the Fellowship that were not hobbits (Aragorn, Boromir, Gandalf, Gimli, and Legolas), along with Faramir and Eomer, the captains of the two cities, will be the mains of your deck.  Why these 7 companions, and not the plethora of others that hang around?  Easy - each has a defining characteristic, special possessions, and a wide range of duplicates for versatality.  Lets go through them.<br />
<br />
Aragorn - His defining characteristic is one of two things... his 8 strength - the highest base of any non-ent companion - and the number of versions that he has.  That means that if you&#39;re looking for a third culture, he&#39;ll fit almost anywhere - and thus you can use that 8 strength and defender +1 abilities, the damage bonuses and card base of Gondor (some denial, archery, skirmish potential, healing, etc.).  He also has that killer 4 vitality, which is so key for double moves against a tough shadow.<br />
<br />
Boromir/Faramir - For Boromir, see Aragorn ... however, he&#39;s only seven strength, and since he&#39;s kinda dead, he doesn&#39;t have as many versions.  Faramir is similar, and more used nowadays as he fits is more recent decks, and has ring-bound versions as well, but both have only 3 vitality.  Vitality enhancers can add to this, but mostly that&#39;s just a card slot that could have been taken up by Aragorn.  They&#39;re useful if they fit your theme better, but often they don&#39;t fit as well as you&#39;d think.<br />
<br />
Gandalf - No other character is so incredible as to merit his own culture, and no other character is more often referred to as &quot;The Man.&quot;  G-Man has so many cards at his disposal that it&#39;s ridiculous, and so many all-in-one deals that you just can&#39;t win against it.  Servant of the Secret Fire.  Trust Me as You Once Did.  Sleep Caradhras, Grown Suddenly Tall.  You thought A Ranger&#39;s Versatality was true versatality - a ranger has got nothing on Gandalf.<br />
First of all, Glamdring, Gandalf&#39;s Staff, Narya, and Shadowfax are his 4 specific possessions.  Gandalf has 4 vitality and 7 strength, so choosing your 2 possessions isn&#39;t really that hard - just tailor it to what your deck needs most.  If it&#39;s skirmishing power and wounding potential, say no more, play Shadowfax or Glamdring with the staff!  If you need the vitality, the exertion space, it&#39;s Narya and the Staff!  Whatever you need, Gandalf always has it handy.  Another point to make is that Gandalf saves card slots - many of his main support cards can be used either directly against your opponent or for any companion - so he&#39;s actually best in combination with other cultures.  The Man definately earned his title.<br />
<br />
Gimli and Legolas - Their job is to kill things.  Note the low strengths but awesome skirmishing possessions and damage bonuses/archery abilities.  We&#39;re also fun to play, and often the cornerstones of our cultures, and should have higher vitality but don&#39;t.<br />
<br />
Eomer - Gimli has met his match!  Fully equipped, Eomer, Third Marshall of the Riddermark can take down any 4 vitality minion in the game with just one or two pumps.  Any fierce minions with wounds on them, or anything that took an archer just dies.  He&#39;s the best skirmishing companion in the game, hands down, and that&#39;s how he should be played.<br />
<br />
All of the above is very important, however, you need to tune your deck to it&#39;s purpose.  If you need to survive, then go with a survival theme, with healing, damage prevention, and some skirmish winning power - you can forsake the damage bonuses, and try to avoid the exertions.  If your goal is to run to 9 like the bejeezes, then you need damage bonuses and strong companions, with a few chumps in there painted red and white with a sign that says &quot;In case of Elephants, Nazgul, or arrows, push me forwards and bury me later.&quot;  This section covered most of the basics of building a good skirmishing deck, and once you&#39;ve built it, it will play itself out of most sticky situations, and testing will reveal flaws and necessary changes.<br />
<br />
Finally, we come to the breakdown - it is the end of this installment where I decide it&#39;s time to go to bed and give you the statistical breakdown of the cards.<br />
<br />
-The result of every skirmish depends upon 3 things:<br />
..Strength<br />
..Vitality<br />
..Damage Bonuses<br />
<br />
-There are six ways a skirmish can end:<br />
..Minion(s) defeated and wounded<br />
..Minion(s) defeated and killed (overwhelm)<br />
..Minion(s) defeated and killed (wounds)<br />
..Companion defeated and wounded<br />
..Companion defeated and killed (overwhelm)<br />
..Companion defeated and killed (wounds)<br />
<br />
For the Free people&#39;s player, the most consistant way to effectively be able to pull out a double move is to kill as many minions as possible while losing no companions and taking wounds to as few companions as possible.  We&#39;re assuming that a double move is the most difficult and best option in every game, as it generally is.  However, certain statistics lend themselves to a double move.  These are:<br />
<br />
 -4 or higher vitality companions-<br />
4 Vitality, as opposed to 3 vitality, doesn&#39;t seem much of an improvement, but if you take 1 wound per double move on this companion, as opposed to the 3 wound companion, with the heal at 3, then you can move all the way to 9 without losing that companion. (1-3w, 3-5w, 5-7ww, 7-9www).  Also, for a minion you can&#39;t beat that doesn&#39;t have a damage bonus - a Nazgul for instance - a 4 vitality companion isn&#39;t in danger of death after skirmishing it 2 times.  As you can see, that extra vitality really makes a difference in the long run.<br />
<br />
 -8 or greater base strength companions-<br />
A companion that is consistantly 10 or greater strength is almost required to kill a powerful minion for a double move, as for the strength 13 Lurtz, 14 Witch King, and 15 Cave Troll, as well as those annying Southrons, an 8 strength companion can use 2 +3 pumps and a weapon to defeat any of them, and a +5 pump from Merry w/ Sword to beat all but the Troll.  Also, so many minions clock in at that Uruk-Hai standard 9 strength that any 10 with weapon companion greatly cuts down the number of card slots needed to maintain skirmishing effeciancy.  Also, most minions that are high in power and reasonably costed do not clock in at 16 strength, and none clock in at 20 or higher, however, many can become 14 and 18, so an 8 strength companion is actually much harder to overwhelm.  Only Faramir, Eomer, Eowyn, Aragorn, Arwen and Gandalf have 8 or greater strength by their own game text, so these are the best skirmishing companions.<br />
-<br />
<br />
It&#39;s over!  Next time, I cover the rest of the phases, and review those Hobtookumps and their skirmishing (or not skirmishing) effectiveness, as well as optimum card choices over other card choices. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5238&view=1&PHPSESSID=ac680a54a4637c3b1c00613f3aea382f'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=ac680a54a4637c3b1c00613f3aea382f'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=ac680a54a4637c3b1c00613f3aea382f'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
